WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:03.510
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:03.510 --> 00:00:22.600
[ Silence ]

00:00:22.600 --> 00:00:24.630
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation: Good afternoon,
everyone, I'm Mark Dimunation,

00:00:24.630 --> 00:00:27.550
I'm chief of the Rare Book and
Special Collections Division.

00:00:27.550 --> 00:00:28.850
Thank you for coming today.

00:00:28.850 --> 00:00:33.570
We're very excited about this, the
Division in the Library of Congress

00:00:33.570 --> 00:00:35.380
at this point have
become old friends

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:37.930
with Saint John's University,
and especially in the making

00:00:37.930 --> 00:00:39.530
of the Saint John's Bible.

00:00:39.530 --> 00:00:42.520
We're very lucky to have Tim
Ternes here today to talk

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:45.620
about the extraordinary
process and the undertaking

00:00:45.620 --> 00:00:49.660
of making this exquisite Bible;
nine years in the making, yes?

00:00:49.660 --> 00:00:50.960
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Fifteen.

00:00:50.960 --> 00:00:52.260
&gt;&gt; Mark Dimunation:
Fifteen years in the making.

00:00:52.260 --> 00:00:58.730
But ten years ago the Library of
Congress featured selected sheets

00:00:58.730 --> 00:01:03.890
from the Pentateuch or the first
books of the Bible, the Psalms,

00:01:03.890 --> 00:01:07.070
and the Gospels, in an
extraordinary exhibition,

00:01:07.070 --> 00:01:09.650
and I might add a very
popular exhibition.

00:01:09.650 --> 00:01:12.740
Today we're going to look
at the further progress.

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:14.560
The Bible is now complete.

00:01:14.560 --> 00:01:19.150
We're very lucky on
this moment to have two

00:01:19.150 --> 00:01:23.660
of what will be seven volumes of
the Apostles facsimile edition.

00:01:23.660 --> 00:01:26.730
This is an extraordinarily
sophisticated facsimile.

00:01:26.730 --> 00:01:30.200 position:56%
We're very lucky here at the Library
of Congress to be the recipient

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:35.340 position:56%
of this, one of the 12, obviously,
Apostles edition that had been made.

00:01:35.340 --> 00:01:38.820
And after the talk,
we'll be happy to,

00:01:38.820 --> 00:01:41.560
as I always say, show you the book.

00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:46.390
[Laughter] And after you hear this
talk, I'm sure you will understand.

00:01:46.390 --> 00:01:49.110
I will be happy to -- we'll
page through the book for you,

00:01:49.110 --> 00:01:51.680
rather than you doing that for
yourself, so we can keep this

00:01:51.680 --> 00:01:55.070
for other generations
to look forward to.

00:01:55.070 --> 00:01:59.920
Tim knows the story of this
Bible in a very intimate way,

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:02.880
and you really have a lovely
talk to look forward to.

00:02:02.880 --> 00:02:05.150
So he's become a good friend.

00:02:05.150 --> 00:02:08.510
Let's welcome here -- welcome him
here to the Library of Congress.

00:02:08.510 --> 00:02:14.030
[ Applause ]

00:02:14.030 --> 00:02:15.330
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Well,
good afternoon, everyone.

00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:16.630
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon.

00:02:16.630 --> 00:02:18.280
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Oh, this is
not Minnesota, that's obvious.

00:02:18.280 --> 00:02:19.720
[Laughter] I said, "Good
afternoon, everyone."

00:02:19.720 --> 00:02:21.020
Gees.

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:22.320
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon.

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:23.620
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: I'm not used
to being tethered to a podium,

00:02:23.620 --> 00:02:25.040
because they've got me tied
here with all these microphones

00:02:25.040 --> 00:02:28.890
and recordings, so I might be a
little awkward with that as well,

00:02:28.890 --> 00:02:31.870
but I'll do my best to stay put
here, which is just killing me

00:02:31.870 --> 00:02:33.610
because I like to be out in
front with everyone else, so.

00:02:33.610 --> 00:02:35.160
It's very nice to be here.

00:02:35.160 --> 00:02:38.390 position:56%
I've actually lectured here before,
and I've shared the project with you

00:02:38.390 --> 00:02:41.350
on many years ago in
2006 when we had it here.

00:02:41.350 --> 00:02:45.100
And I have for you just
an outstanding story;

00:02:45.100 --> 00:02:48.450
an outstanding story,
that's been 500 years

00:02:48.450 --> 00:02:50.370
since it's been able to be told.

00:02:50.370 --> 00:02:52.540
Because the last time a
monastery did something

00:02:52.540 --> 00:02:54.790
like this really was 500 years ago.

00:02:54.790 --> 00:02:57.680
And I always tell people we
now know why it took 500 years

00:02:57.680 --> 00:03:01.380 position:56%
to do it again; [laughter] because
it's an incredibly huge undertaking.

00:03:01.380 --> 00:03:04.130
And it's also a fascinating story.

00:03:04.130 --> 00:03:07.180
Now, I'm the director of the Saint
John's Bible, which simply means

00:03:07.180 --> 00:03:11.120
that I am the keeper of the pages,
and the keeper of the story.

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:13.130
And it really is a
good job, trust me.

00:03:13.130 --> 00:03:14.430
I love what I do.

00:03:14.430 --> 00:03:15.980
I wasn't always the director
of the Saint John's Bible.

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:18.470
For 17 years I was an
elementary classroom teacher.

00:03:18.470 --> 00:03:22.710
So truly one day I was doing
playground duty for one day,

00:03:22.710 --> 00:03:25.390 position:56%
and then a few months later I was
lecturing at the Library of Congress

00:03:25.390 --> 00:03:27.280
and thought, "Life has changed."

00:03:27.280 --> 00:03:30.000
The behavior patterns didn't
really change between the two.

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:32.000
[Laughter] But trust me, life
has changed for me as well.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.400
And now I'm back again, and
it's really quite a treat.

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:37.670
Because the story of the Saint
John's Bible, it hasn't been able

00:03:37.670 --> 00:03:41.810
to be told for many generations,
is a fascinating story,

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:44.520
but it's also not our story.

00:03:44.520 --> 00:03:46.350
Because many people don't realize,

00:03:46.350 --> 00:03:49.840
this thing called "The Saint John's
Bible", which we are so famous for,

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:51.890
and which is so famous
in its own rite,

00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:53.600
is something that Saint
John's never thought

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:55.850
about doing; never wanted to do.

00:03:55.850 --> 00:03:59.930
As I always say, "We
will never do it again."

00:03:59.930 --> 00:04:02.790
Because it wasn't our idea.

00:04:02.790 --> 00:04:05.620
The Saint John's Bible is something
we didn't think about doing,

00:04:05.620 --> 00:04:08.070
it was the brainchild
of this man right here.

00:04:08.070 --> 00:04:11.160
Now, just so you realize,
that is not a picture of me.

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:13.430
[Laughter] Many people
say I look just like him.

00:04:13.430 --> 00:04:15.940 position:56%
I have been walking -- this is true,
I've been walking down the streets

00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:19.580
of London, and I have been asked
for Donald Jackson's autograph.

00:04:19.580 --> 00:04:21.460
The man is 75 years old.

00:04:21.460 --> 00:04:24.230
I don't know how I feel about that,
but it's the shared body trait

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:25.670
that we have here as well, so.

00:04:25.670 --> 00:04:28.790
Donald Jackson, world-renowned
individual.

00:04:28.790 --> 00:04:30.090
He's a calligrapher.

00:04:30.090 --> 00:04:31.390
And you think about that.

00:04:31.390 --> 00:04:34.540
He has made his fame and his
fortune with something every one

00:04:34.540 --> 00:04:37.350
of you in this audience can do.

00:04:37.350 --> 00:04:38.650
You can all make letters.

00:04:38.650 --> 00:04:39.950
Think about that.

00:04:39.950 --> 00:04:42.260
Now, some make nicer
letters than others.

00:04:42.260 --> 00:04:43.880
I make letters.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:45.400
We can all do what he does.

00:04:45.400 --> 00:04:47.850
But I doubt any of us are
going to have an exhibition

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:50.580
of our handwriting
that travels the globe.

00:04:50.580 --> 00:04:53.000
I doubt any of us are going
to line up around the block

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:54.390
to look at our own handwriting.

00:04:54.390 --> 00:04:57.030
And I doubt the Queen of
England is going to hire you

00:04:57.030 --> 00:04:59.260
to be her professional scribe.

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:01.160
Because that's Donald's real job.

00:05:01.160 --> 00:05:03.160
Donald is by profession
the senior scribe

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:06.430
to Her Royal Majesty's Crown Office
in the House of Lords in London.

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:07.730
Quite a long title.

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:10.040
He's the -- he's often called
the Queen's calligrapher.

00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:11.660
He's not -- that's
not really his job.

00:05:11.660 --> 00:05:13.180 position:56%
He writes things that she gives out.

00:05:13.180 --> 00:05:16.310
So, for example, he
did the Royal Charter

00:05:16.310 --> 00:05:18.950
that made Margaret
Thatcher Dame of the Realm.

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:21.650
He did Charles and
Diana's wedding papers.

00:05:21.650 --> 00:05:23.820
He did Charles and
Diana's divorce papers,

00:05:23.820 --> 00:05:25.120
[laughter] and all those things.

00:05:25.120 --> 00:05:28.200
He did not do William and
Kate's wedding certificate.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:31.250
The only one he did not do;
because he was finishing --

00:05:31.250 --> 00:05:34.090
and we pressed him to finish the
Saint John's Bible at that time.

00:05:34.090 --> 00:05:36.190
So we beat out the
future king of England

00:05:36.190 --> 00:05:37.490
and his wife all the way through.

00:05:37.490 --> 00:05:40.700
But the story of the Saint
John's Bible is Donald's story,

00:05:40.700 --> 00:05:43.250
because it was his idea.

00:05:43.250 --> 00:05:46.940
Donald talked about really
having a dream of wanting

00:05:46.940 --> 00:05:48.800
to handwrite scripture
from a lot earlier

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:50.650
than anyone can ever even imagine.

00:05:50.650 --> 00:05:54.530
In fact, Donald talks about
being a child and falling

00:05:54.530 --> 00:05:56.480
in love with calligraphy.

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:00.310
Now, think what you used to do when
you were ten, 12, 13 years old.

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:02.600
[ Silence ]

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:05.920
And I doubt you spent time
doing what Donald did.

00:06:05.920 --> 00:06:09.190
One of his favorite activities
would be to go to a local museum,

00:06:09.190 --> 00:06:12.590
or library, go to the rare book
room, which of course you had here,

00:06:12.590 --> 00:06:15.430
or the manuscript room and he
said, "I would look at the cases

00:06:15.430 --> 00:06:17.540
and I would copy what I saw."

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:20.750
He said, "I would spend hours
sitting in places like this looking

00:06:20.750 --> 00:06:24.130
in the cases, and recreating,"
not tracing, but recreating.

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:26.690
And he said, "I loved it."

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:28.020
Now, think about that.

00:06:28.020 --> 00:06:30.300
And then look at this.

00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:34.650
That's a letter M that Donald did
when he was about 12 years old.

00:06:34.650 --> 00:06:37.420
[Murmuring] I was still
coloring inside the lines

00:06:37.420 --> 00:06:38.720
when I was 12 years old.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:40.020
[Laughter] Half the
time outside the lines.

00:06:40.020 --> 00:06:41.320
That's amazing when
you look at that.

00:06:41.320 --> 00:06:42.950
Here's a piece he did a
couple of years later.

00:06:42.950 --> 00:06:44.310
And it does belong sideways.

00:06:44.310 --> 00:06:45.910 position:56%
It's called "The Reclining Madonna".

00:06:45.910 --> 00:06:49.940
But look at the difference in
skill already that that child --

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:53.220
I emphasize that, that
that child has developed.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:55.350
And he said it was by
going in and looking

00:06:55.350 --> 00:06:57.100
at the way the artist
bent the lines,

00:06:57.100 --> 00:06:58.640
laid their gold, blended
their color.

00:06:58.640 --> 00:07:00.500 position:56%
He said, "By looking at the masters,

00:07:00.500 --> 00:07:03.390
that's how I became
a master myself."

00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:05.190
What a great lesson for all of us.

00:07:05.190 --> 00:07:08.570
And it was right around this time
in his life Donald Jackson said,

00:07:08.570 --> 00:07:12.150
"You know, I'm not trying to brag,
but I remember very clearly,"

00:07:12.150 --> 00:07:14.840
he said, "looking at
something I had done one day,

00:07:14.840 --> 00:07:17.020
and it was like a light
bulb went off."

00:07:17.020 --> 00:07:20.690
And he said, "I realized I'm good."

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:23.930
And it just -- it's like, "I
can do this, and I love it."

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:27.460
And right around age
13, 13, 14, he saw --

00:07:27.460 --> 00:07:30.130
he talks about sitting
down with a piece of paper

00:07:30.130 --> 00:07:32.570
and writing two goals for his life.

00:07:32.570 --> 00:07:37.030
Now, think about that, what
did you want to do at age 13?

00:07:37.030 --> 00:07:39.080
[Laughs] I taught elementary
school for 17 years.

00:07:39.080 --> 00:07:42.280
I never once met a child who had
goals, number one, but [inaudible].

00:07:42.280 --> 00:07:46.060
But he sat down and said
on this piece of paper,

00:07:46.060 --> 00:07:48.900
"When I'm old enough, I want to
work for the Queen of England."

00:07:48.900 --> 00:07:50.760
That happened in his 20s, one

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:53.060
of the youngest people ever
employed as a royal scribe.

00:07:53.060 --> 00:07:54.980
And number two -- I bet you can
guess what the other thing is

00:07:54.980 --> 00:07:56.280
on that page.

00:07:56.280 --> 00:07:59.590 position:56%
It said, "When I practice long and
hard -- " and it's a paraphrase but,

00:07:59.590 --> 00:08:01.260
"I practice long and hard, I want

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:05.580
to do what calligraphers have
always done, handwrite scripture."

00:08:05.580 --> 00:08:07.100
Think about that.

00:08:07.100 --> 00:08:08.400
What a goal.

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:11.960
Now, the first one he got -- he
managed to make happen in his 20s.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:16.210
But the second one took almost
50 years to become a reality.

00:08:16.210 --> 00:08:18.560
So this was his childhood dream.

00:08:18.560 --> 00:08:21.810
And he needed a partner to make it
happen, because as you can imagine,

00:08:21.810 --> 00:08:24.090
this is a huge undertaking.

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:28.190
Well, so we have this man over in
Wales with this childhood dream.

00:08:28.190 --> 00:08:31.180
And then we end up with a
bunch of monks in the middle

00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:33.880
of the cornfields of
Minnesota with a vision.

00:08:33.880 --> 00:08:36.650
And we have to get the two
of them together somehow.

00:08:36.650 --> 00:08:39.040
And do you know what
the catalyst was?

00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:41.070
[ Silence ]

00:08:41.070 --> 00:08:42.570
Something you all love and use --

00:08:42.570 --> 00:08:44.770
[ Silence ]

00:08:44.770 --> 00:08:46.630
But it was rocking Donald's world.

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:50.070
In the 1980s something
changed his world dramatically.

00:08:50.070 --> 00:08:52.130
[ Silence ]

00:08:52.130 --> 00:08:57.700
The computer; [laughter] because
in the 1980s what came into vogue,

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:01.850
everyone was now an
electronic calligrapher.

00:09:01.850 --> 00:09:03.150
You no longer needed Donald.

00:09:03.150 --> 00:09:07.360 position:56%
And as Donald always says, "Everyone
had at their fingertips the true,

00:09:07.360 --> 00:09:11.340
dirtiest four-letter F-word in
the English language, the font."

00:09:11.340 --> 00:09:13.120 position:56%
[Laughter] Because what do you have;

00:09:13.120 --> 00:09:16.860
you can now have 50,000
ways to do his job.

00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:19.300
So calligraphy as an
art form was waning.

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:23.670 position:56%
And so right around that time a
group of calligraphers in the middle

00:09:23.670 --> 00:09:25.440
of Minnesota said,
"We've got to find a way

00:09:25.440 --> 00:09:26.740
to stop this from happening.

00:09:26.740 --> 00:09:30.690 position:56%
How can we share the passion that we
have for our art form with others?

00:09:30.690 --> 00:09:32.650
Let's see if we can hold
a calligraphy conference

00:09:32.650 --> 00:09:36.020 position:56%
and get maybe 30, 40, 50 people, the
top artists from around the world

00:09:36.020 --> 00:09:39.620
to come to Minnesota and talk
about the future of our art.

00:09:39.620 --> 00:09:41.440
And to do that we're
going to need a big name."

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:43.770
So they contacted Donald Jackson.

00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:46.370
And they said, "Donald,
would you come to Minnesota

00:09:46.370 --> 00:09:48.400
and teach a calligraphy
course, and help us deal

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:52.270
with this idea of our
waning art form?"

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:54.980
And one of the organizers had
a grandson that happened to go

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:57.930
to school at Saint John's
University in Collegeville.

00:09:57.930 --> 00:10:01.600
And they said, "I know the perfect
place where we can have this."

00:10:01.600 --> 00:10:05.720
They hired Donald Jackson, and
in 1981 he came to the campus.

00:10:05.720 --> 00:10:08.840
And they got a few more
than 30 or 40 people.

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:10.550
[Laughter] Five hundred
calligraphers came

00:10:10.550 --> 00:10:13.320
from around the world, and
they turned our gymnasium

00:10:13.320 --> 00:10:15.280
into the world's largest
scriptorium.

00:10:15.280 --> 00:10:18.600
They put Donald on the stage, he'd
make a letter A and they'd go wild.

00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:19.900
I'm serious.

00:10:19.900 --> 00:10:21.200
[Laughter] He'd make a letter
B and they'd drool and scream.

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:23.180
It was amazing.

00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:26.190
But what was most important
is that's how Donald got

00:10:26.190 --> 00:10:28.200
to Saint John's.

00:10:28.200 --> 00:10:30.600
And the reason the Bible
is at Saint John's is

00:10:30.600 --> 00:10:34.580
because Donald Jackson countered
something and saw something there

00:10:34.580 --> 00:10:39.550
that every person who comes on the
campus sees and blows them away.

00:10:39.550 --> 00:10:42.560
Now, has anyone ever been to Saint
John's in Collegeville, Minnesota?

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:43.860
A couple of you here, yes.

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:45.660 position:56%
What's the first thing you encounter
when you come on the campus?

00:10:45.660 --> 00:10:48.270
[ Silence ]

00:10:48.270 --> 00:10:52.820
This. This is our world-famous
Abby Church.

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:55.860
In the 1950s, this community

00:10:55.860 --> 00:10:58.290
of monks hired Marcel
Broyer [assumed spelling],

00:10:58.290 --> 00:11:00.220
one of the first kind of --

00:11:00.220 --> 00:11:02.600
or one of the big names
in the Modernist Movement

00:11:02.600 --> 00:11:04.450
to design and build their church.

00:11:04.450 --> 00:11:07.610
And the inside is even more
incredible than the outside.

00:11:07.610 --> 00:11:10.830
And this incredibly beautiful
mid-century modern church sits

00:11:10.830 --> 00:11:14.020 position:56%
in the middle of the campus, with
this huge presence, and Donald said,

00:11:14.020 --> 00:11:15.970
"I never knew it was there."

00:11:15.970 --> 00:11:17.270
He never knew it was there.

00:11:17.270 --> 00:11:20.330
It's an amazing building and he
said, "I went in, and I stood there

00:11:20.330 --> 00:11:23.710
in the middle of that church on my
very first visit looking around,

00:11:23.710 --> 00:11:28.270
and I said, to myself,
'Wow, these guys get it'."

00:11:28.270 --> 00:11:31.570
And he said, "They
understand quality,

00:11:31.570 --> 00:11:32.950
and they understand longevity.

00:11:32.950 --> 00:11:34.310
And not to be funny," he said,

00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:38.780
"but I had concrete proof
as to how they thought."

00:11:38.780 --> 00:11:40.080
[Laughter] Because here it is.

