00:28:06.430 --> 00:28:08.930
And before everyone gets mad
at me, we did not kill a bunch

00:28:08.930 --> 00:28:10.420
of baby cows for the Bible.

00:28:10.420 --> 00:28:14.020
We do not have a herd hidden behind
the ivy church branded "Genesis,

00:28:14.020 --> 00:28:16.520
Exodus, Leviticus,
Numbers" and so on.

00:28:16.520 --> 00:28:19.490
[Laughter] This came from veal
production in the United Kingdom.

00:28:19.490 --> 00:28:23.210
And as you look at this -- and the
manufacturer's name was "Colia,

00:28:23.210 --> 00:28:25.230
Colia Pegnel" [phonetic],
which is a great name.

00:28:25.230 --> 00:28:29.020 position:56%
And they make parchment, and velum,
and so on for the houses, Parliament

00:28:29.020 --> 00:28:31.210
and so on, and different
documentation.

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:33.970
But what the benefit of
this beautiful surface is,

00:28:33.970 --> 00:28:37.340
is that it's incredibly durable.

00:28:37.340 --> 00:28:42.630
But most importantly, it's
going to last a long time.

00:28:42.630 --> 00:28:46.360
But it's got a special
benefit for us humans.

00:28:46.360 --> 00:28:48.700
[ Silence ]

00:28:48.700 --> 00:28:50.000
Ah, think about that.

00:28:50.000 --> 00:28:51.480
You'll find our later, if you
haven't thought about it yet.

00:28:51.480 --> 00:28:55.400
It's because we're human
we love this stuff.

00:28:55.400 --> 00:28:56.700
Think about that.

00:28:56.700 --> 00:28:58.610
Now, as you're feeling -- as you're
petting the cow as it comes around,

00:28:58.610 --> 00:29:01.650
all right, did you notice
that one side feels fuzzy,

00:29:01.650 --> 00:29:03.470
and one side feels smooth?

00:29:03.470 --> 00:29:06.930
Well, that's the inside
and outside of the cow.

00:29:06.930 --> 00:29:10.410
And my question for you as
a scribe, "On which side

00:29:10.410 --> 00:29:12.510
of the skin are you going to
write for the pages of the book?"

00:29:12.510 --> 00:29:15.190
[ Silence ]

00:29:15.190 --> 00:29:17.370
[ Inaudible Comments ]

00:29:17.370 --> 00:29:18.670
&gt;&gt; Both.

00:29:18.670 --> 00:29:19.970
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Oh,
someone's thinking; yes, both.

00:29:19.970 --> 00:29:22.190
You turn the pages of
a book, don't you, yes.

00:29:22.190 --> 00:29:24.630
So you're going to write
on both sides of the skin.

00:29:24.630 --> 00:29:28.700
So forgive my paper skin
here, but this is one --

00:29:28.700 --> 00:29:31.690
this is about the size
of a skin on the calf.

00:29:31.690 --> 00:29:33.170
And we fold it in half.

00:29:33.170 --> 00:29:37.360
And from one skin we get four
pages in the Saint John's Bible,

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:40.450
which also gives us
the size of our book.

00:29:40.450 --> 00:29:42.790
But there's a reason
we have a big book.

00:29:42.790 --> 00:29:45.870
And it's a theological reason.

00:29:45.870 --> 00:29:49.130
Because we could have saved
a lot of cows if we folded

00:29:49.130 --> 00:29:51.390
that in half again, and
half again, and half again.

00:29:51.390 --> 00:29:53.980
We could have gotten 32 pages
from one poor little cow.

00:29:53.980 --> 00:29:55.780
But why didn't we?

00:29:55.780 --> 00:29:59.010
[ Silence ]

00:29:59.010 --> 00:30:00.490
[ Whispering ]

00:30:00.490 --> 00:30:02.110
Why didn't we?

00:30:02.110 --> 00:30:04.210
[ Inaudible Comments ]

00:30:04.210 --> 00:30:06.330
The size of the script
would be very small.

00:30:06.330 --> 00:30:09.030
But you know what,
go up in archives.

00:30:09.030 --> 00:30:12.390
You'll see tiny, tiny print
that's really quite amazing.

00:30:12.390 --> 00:30:14.880
And actually we have some pages
that are written pretty tiny.

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:17.010 position:56%
Why wouldn't we do a book like this?

00:30:17.010 --> 00:30:18.790
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:30:18.790 --> 00:30:20.090
&gt;&gt; Pardon?

00:30:20.090 --> 00:30:21.390
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:30:21.390 --> 00:30:22.910
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Yes; but there's
-- it's -- play with that.

00:30:22.910 --> 00:30:24.210
&gt;&gt; It won't last.

00:30:24.210 --> 00:30:26.630
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Well, if
it's the same materials.

00:30:26.630 --> 00:30:30.090
But think about it,
what does this say?

00:30:30.090 --> 00:30:33.140
It actually says the same
thing that this says.

00:30:33.140 --> 00:30:35.270
[ Silence ]

00:30:35.270 --> 00:30:37.010
Who is this for?

00:30:37.010 --> 00:30:38.310
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:30:38.310 --> 00:30:42.100
This is -- in fact I even
use this like this, don't I?

00:30:42.100 --> 00:30:43.400
[Laughter] Think about that.

00:30:43.400 --> 00:30:47.520
Think about what this
says, and who is this for?

00:30:47.520 --> 00:30:49.010
Who's this for?

00:30:49.010 --> 00:30:50.310
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:30:50.310 --> 00:30:52.310
This is mine.

00:30:52.310 --> 00:30:55.960
And one of the major reasons we
did the Saint John's Bible is

00:30:55.960 --> 00:31:00.080
to remind us that, you know,
even this says, "This is mine."

00:31:00.080 --> 00:31:03.880
But what does this say?

00:31:03.880 --> 00:31:06.000
[Laughter] This says, "You
can't even lift me by yourself."

00:31:06.000 --> 00:31:07.300
I mean, think about that.

00:31:07.300 --> 00:31:09.500
What does this say;
this says it is --

00:31:09.500 --> 00:31:10.800
&gt;&gt; Ours.

00:31:10.800 --> 00:31:12.100
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Ours;
it's collectively ours.

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:13.880
And one of the main
theological elements

00:31:13.880 --> 00:31:17.340 position:56%
of the Saint John's Bible is that
we did this project to remind people

00:31:17.340 --> 00:31:19.660
that the Bible is communal.

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:23.360
And what says more communal
than something very large?

00:31:23.360 --> 00:31:25.910
And as you said, sir, magnificent.

00:31:25.910 --> 00:31:29.170
In fact, because it's communal,
and because it's so big,

00:31:29.170 --> 00:31:31.780
it cannot even possibly
be one volume.

00:31:31.780 --> 00:31:35.530
The Saint John's Bible
takes seven books this size

00:31:35.530 --> 00:31:38.110
to make the entire
Old and New Testament.

00:31:38.110 --> 00:31:42.640
And so imagine what it says on
the first time the Bible is bound

00:31:42.640 --> 00:31:44.990
and carried into the Abby Church,

00:31:44.990 --> 00:31:48.140
well it takes 14 people
to carry the Bible.

00:31:48.140 --> 00:31:49.440
[Laughter] Wow.

00:31:49.440 --> 00:31:52.200
Does that ever make a
statement about the importance

00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:53.500
of what we think about this?

00:31:53.500 --> 00:31:57.010
And also, the importance of
it as a communal work of art.

00:31:57.010 --> 00:32:01.220
And in fact that's the
primary reason we did this;

00:32:01.220 --> 00:32:06.220
is yes to ignite the imagination,
yes to celebrate the millennium.

00:32:06.220 --> 00:32:08.150
But to remind us as a people

00:32:08.150 --> 00:32:13.750
that this is a communal work
that's best experienced shared.

00:32:13.750 --> 00:32:18.990 position:56%
We could spend truly the rest of the
afternoon talking about the minutia

00:32:18.990 --> 00:32:22.710
that went into the layout of the
pages, the design of everything.

00:32:22.710 --> 00:32:24.940
Because the detail that went

00:32:24.940 --> 00:32:28.150
into making the original
is almost overwhelming.

00:32:28.150 --> 00:32:29.530
There's one last thing
we should talk

00:32:29.530 --> 00:32:31.680
about before going into the book.

00:32:31.680 --> 00:32:35.350
And that was the most difficult
decision in the entire project.

00:32:35.350 --> 00:32:36.650
And do you know what that is?

00:32:36.650 --> 00:32:37.950
&gt;&gt; Writing it.

00:32:37.950 --> 00:32:39.250
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Pardon?

00:32:39.250 --> 00:32:40.550
&gt;&gt; Writing it?

00:32:40.550 --> 00:32:41.850
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: You're close.

00:32:41.850 --> 00:32:43.150
We always knew it was
going to be English.

00:32:43.150 --> 00:32:44.450
&gt;&gt; Translating?

00:32:44.450 --> 00:32:45.750
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Which translation
do we use; because no matter

00:32:45.750 --> 00:32:49.260 position:56%
which translation we choose, it will
be the wrong one, simple as that.

00:32:49.260 --> 00:32:50.560
We know what that's like.

00:32:50.560 --> 00:32:53.210
Well, we had a lot of thought into
this, and we wanted a translation

00:32:53.210 --> 00:32:55.440
that was literal, that was
scholarly, that was inclusive,

00:32:55.440 --> 00:32:57.960
that was approved for use by
the Catholic Church and so on.

00:32:57.960 --> 00:32:59.330
We are Roman Catholic.

00:32:59.330 --> 00:33:02.650
But we wanted it to be a
translation that was used

00:33:02.650 --> 00:33:05.300
by as many others as possible.

00:33:05.300 --> 00:33:06.910
And so with that in
mind, we chose to go

00:33:06.910 --> 00:33:10.080
with the New Revised
Standard Version, or the NRSV.

00:33:10.080 --> 00:33:12.310
And that has become the
most perfect choice for us.

00:33:12.310 --> 00:33:13.610
It is literal.

00:33:13.610 --> 00:33:14.910
It is scholarly.

00:33:14.910 --> 00:33:16.210
It's inclusive.

00:33:16.210 --> 00:33:18.750
But many of you may or may not know
that the NRSV happens to be one

00:33:18.750 --> 00:33:21.890
of the only translations
of the Bible in English

00:33:21.890 --> 00:33:23.220
that is officially approved for use

00:33:23.220 --> 00:33:26.020
by almost every major
Christian church worldwide.

00:33:26.020 --> 00:33:29.550
And many non-Christian
traditions when

00:33:29.550 --> 00:33:33.660 position:56%
and if they ever need a translation,
will often go to the NRSV.

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:36.430
Now, it's very seldom
that other traditions do,

00:33:36.430 --> 00:33:38.100
but they will often use that one.

00:33:38.100 --> 00:33:40.720
And so it has become the
most perfect choice for us.

00:33:40.720 --> 00:33:44.010
Now, it is the entire
Old and New Testament,

00:33:44.010 --> 00:33:47.430
all 73 Books of the Bible.

00:33:47.430 --> 00:33:49.930
Even a few that some of you
might have left out at one time.

00:33:49.930 --> 00:33:51.230
Just keep that in mind.

00:33:51.230 --> 00:33:52.820
It includes the apocryphal
books as well.

00:33:52.820 --> 00:33:55.440
In the Catholic tradition
we include the apocryphal,

00:33:55.440 --> 00:33:58.440
or the [inaudible] Books
as well in the canon.

00:33:58.440 --> 00:34:01.220
Other than that, it's like every
other NRSV you've ever read,

00:34:01.220 --> 00:34:02.610
or ever seen.

00:34:02.610 --> 00:34:07.220
Ours is just a lot
prettier, all the way through.

00:34:07.220 --> 00:34:11.090
Now, along with these
beautifully handwritten pages,

00:34:11.090 --> 00:34:12.660
and this whole idea
of a communal work,

00:34:12.660 --> 00:34:18.140
we wanted to bring the Saint John's
Bible into a new translation,

00:34:18.140 --> 00:34:21.650
but not a word translation,
a visual translation.

00:34:21.650 --> 00:34:23.960
And so what we did
is we incorporated

00:34:23.960 --> 00:34:29.990 position:56%
over 160 artworks designed to bring
the Scriptures into the modern world

00:34:29.990 --> 00:34:31.350
through the way that many people

00:34:31.350 --> 00:34:34.520
in the modern world experience
almost everything nowadays,

00:34:34.520 --> 00:34:36.200
visually.

00:34:36.200 --> 00:34:38.320
So for the remainder of our
time, we're going to look

00:34:38.320 --> 00:34:39.620
at a few of the artworks.

00:34:39.620 --> 00:34:41.670
Actually, we're going to get you
looking at a few of the artworks.

00:34:41.670 --> 00:34:44.540
And we don't have time to read the
passages today, so I've chosen one

00:34:44.540 --> 00:34:49.450
that I bet almost everyone in this
room knows, even if you are --

00:34:49.450 --> 00:34:53.350
even if you've never read the
Bible, or the Torah, or the Koran.

00:34:53.350 --> 00:34:57.270
Even if you're a strong believer,
or not a believer at all,

00:34:57.270 --> 00:35:02.050
if you're a skeptic, or, you
know, a hardcore literalist,

00:35:02.050 --> 00:35:04.020
I bet you know the Creation story.

00:35:04.020 --> 00:35:07.030
Think about it.

00:35:07.030 --> 00:35:10.940 position:56%
Because I bet I could stop the first
stranger on the street, and ask him

00:35:10.940 --> 00:35:13.870
or her by biblical
or torah tradition,

00:35:13.870 --> 00:35:15.450
how many days are in Creation.

00:35:15.450 --> 00:35:17.920
And almost everyone's
going to answer seven.

00:35:17.920 --> 00:35:19.500
Even if they never read it.

00:35:19.500 --> 00:35:22.500
I could ask the next stranger on
the street and ask them by biblical

00:35:22.500 --> 00:35:24.790
or torah tradition who are
the first human beings,

00:35:24.790 --> 00:35:27.220
and almost everyone's going
to answer, "Adam and Eve."

00:35:27.220 --> 00:35:30.480
Because those passages,
those stories that are shared

00:35:30.480 --> 00:35:34.610
by many traditions, are as
much a part of popular culture

00:35:34.610 --> 00:35:36.000
as they are religious culture.

00:35:36.000 --> 00:35:40.180
In fact, we have court cases taking
place right now about them as well.

00:35:40.180 --> 00:35:44.150
They're some of the most argued
about passages in the Bible.

00:35:44.150 --> 00:35:48.570
Bow, let's keep all that in mind,
and then pretend for a few moments

00:35:48.570 --> 00:35:51.270
that you are the artist
for the Saint John's Bible,

00:35:51.270 --> 00:35:55.360
and Saint John's has
come to you and said,

00:35:55.360 --> 00:35:57.450
"We want you -- " we've
chosen Creation.

00:35:57.450 --> 00:36:00.160
Now, we know Creation has already
been shown a thousand times

00:36:00.160 --> 00:36:01.460
throughout history.

00:36:01.460 --> 00:36:02.760
There are probably
more images of Creation

00:36:02.760 --> 00:36:04.590
