00:50:08.020 --> 00:50:09.450
on how to do his or her work?

00:50:09.450 --> 00:50:10.750
[Laughter] Mmm.

00:50:10.750 --> 00:50:12.510
They would email that over to
the artist, because remember,

00:50:12.510 --> 00:50:16.420
Saint John's is in Minnesota, the
artists are in Monolith, Wales.

00:50:16.420 --> 00:50:20.720
They would get those, begin
their own scripture study,

00:50:20.720 --> 00:50:23.990
begin playing with the notes, and
then they would start sketching.

00:50:23.990 --> 00:50:26.290
Here is the sketch for Creation.

00:50:26.290 --> 00:50:28.230
Sometimes they would
make it in collage form

00:50:28.230 --> 00:50:30.590
so they could move things around.

00:50:30.590 --> 00:50:32.560
Then they would sometimes
just do it in sketches.

00:50:32.560 --> 00:50:36.250
Here are sketches and
-- for Adam and Eve.

00:50:36.250 --> 00:50:40.330
[Clears Throat] They would do
these sketches, make a mockup,

00:50:40.330 --> 00:50:44.120
and then take pictures of it and
email the pictures to Saint John's.

00:50:44.120 --> 00:50:46.680
The committee at Saint
John's would look at them,

00:50:46.680 --> 00:50:49.220 position:56%
and type up feedback for the artist.

00:50:49.220 --> 00:50:50.890
They'd email the artist
the feedback,

00:50:50.890 --> 00:50:52.280
the artist would roll his eyes.

00:50:52.280 --> 00:50:54.570
[Laughter] [Clears Throat]
And type up feedback

00:50:54.570 --> 00:50:56.520
on our feedback, and
email it back to us.

00:50:56.520 --> 00:50:58.560
We roll our eyes, and
type up feedback

00:50:58.560 --> 00:51:00.250
on his feedback, and mail it back.

00:51:00.250 --> 00:51:03.680
And we'd go back and forth like
that for anywhere between four

00:51:03.680 --> 00:51:07.370
to eight months for
every single image.

00:51:07.370 --> 00:51:11.000
Once both sides of the ocean
said, "These are theologically

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:13.690
and artistically sound,"
not right, but sound,

00:51:13.690 --> 00:51:16.340
then they would do
them on the velum.

00:51:16.340 --> 00:51:20.500
And that's how they actually
look side by side in the Bible.

00:51:20.500 --> 00:51:22.260
Absolutely beautiful.

00:51:22.260 --> 00:51:26.060
Take that process times
160 artworks,

00:51:26.060 --> 00:51:30.860
and you can see why this
took 15 years to create.

00:51:30.860 --> 00:51:32.160
Pretty amazing.

00:51:32.160 --> 00:51:35.960
Now, along with the beautiful
pages of elegant artworks,

00:51:35.960 --> 00:51:40.440
most of the work of the Saint
John's Bible is 1130 some pages

00:51:40.440 --> 00:51:43.300
of elegant text.

00:51:43.300 --> 00:51:46.750
And here is this page, and
the first thing you'll notice,

00:51:46.750 --> 00:51:50.520
and your first thing you'll learn
when you look at a page like this,

00:51:50.520 --> 00:51:55.700
is that you never call this a font.

00:51:55.700 --> 00:51:59.220
[Laughter] This is a script;
or as Mark said, "A hand."

00:51:59.220 --> 00:52:01.440
Because a computer does a font,

00:52:01.440 --> 00:52:03.860
or a machine does a font,
or it's a created thing.

00:52:03.860 --> 00:52:06.560
This is a hand, a beautifully
written hand.

00:52:06.560 --> 00:52:09.510
There are six calligraphers
in the Saint John's Bible,

00:52:09.510 --> 00:52:11.430
each of them working to
make sure their hands looked

00:52:11.430 --> 00:52:13.520
as much alike as possible.

00:52:13.520 --> 00:52:15.940
But you can tell the difference.

00:52:15.940 --> 00:52:17.370
Look at their tails.

00:52:17.370 --> 00:52:19.400
Look at their pressure.

00:52:19.400 --> 00:52:23.850 position:56%
And the humanity of a hand comes out
very easily, and very beautifully.

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:26.880
You'll also see that throughout
the Saint John's Bible,

00:52:26.880 --> 00:52:32.040
the very beginning we use flora
and fauna from Africa, Mesopotamia,

00:52:32.040 --> 00:52:36.280
the Middle East, because of course
that's what most likely it probably

00:52:36.280 --> 00:52:37.630
started there.

00:52:37.630 --> 00:52:40.250
But as you turn the pages
in the Saint John's Bible,

00:52:40.250 --> 00:52:42.580
for most of the rest
of the book, the plants

00:52:42.580 --> 00:52:45.430
and animals come from
Central Minnesota.

00:52:45.430 --> 00:52:48.250
[Laughter] And we change all
the "amens" to "Yes, sure,

00:52:48.250 --> 00:52:51.000
you bet you" for the
whole Bible as well so.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:52.870
[Laughter] We didn't change
a word, trust me, trust me.

00:52:52.870 --> 00:52:57.310
But we do weave those things
just as they would centuries ago

00:52:57.310 --> 00:52:58.610
into the pages of the bible

00:52:58.610 --> 00:53:01.370
so it geographically
grounds it in our work.

00:53:01.370 --> 00:53:04.340
Now, a page of script like
this takes one calligrapher

00:53:04.340 --> 00:53:07.430
between seven to 13 hours to write.

00:53:07.430 --> 00:53:08.980
Think about that.

00:53:08.980 --> 00:53:11.220
[ Silence ]

00:53:11.220 --> 00:53:13.140
And then we also get
the common question --

00:53:13.140 --> 00:53:15.270
[ Silence ]

00:53:15.270 --> 00:53:17.950
"What happens if you
make a mistake?"

00:53:17.950 --> 00:53:19.250
You are human.

00:53:19.250 --> 00:53:22.440
And remember I said you're very
happy you're working on a cow.

00:53:22.440 --> 00:53:24.740
[Paper Sound] Because
cows are very forgiving.

00:53:24.740 --> 00:53:27.510
If you make a mistake in
the Saint John's Bible,

00:53:27.510 --> 00:53:29.470
you go right back to your process.

00:53:29.470 --> 00:53:33.190
Take your knife, scrape it away,
take sandpaper and sand it off,

00:53:33.190 --> 00:53:35.420
and you will never
know it was there.

00:53:35.420 --> 00:53:36.720
Isn't that amazing?

00:53:36.720 --> 00:53:39.240
That's one of the very big
benefits of using the velum.

00:53:39.240 --> 00:53:42.960
However, let's say you make a
mistake in the same place again.

00:53:42.960 --> 00:53:47.660
Or let's pretend that you
left out an entire line,

00:53:47.660 --> 00:53:49.750
and you don't catch it until later.

00:53:49.750 --> 00:53:53.050
And, remember, if I
make a mistake here,

00:53:53.050 --> 00:53:54.690
I've made a mistake on four pages.

00:53:54.690 --> 00:53:56.980
So you don't throw it away.

00:53:56.980 --> 00:53:59.800
So sometimes you make a mistake
that's too big to cover up,

00:53:59.800 --> 00:54:03.410
and if you do, you turn
it into something nice.

00:54:03.410 --> 00:54:06.640
Here is the very first mistake
in the Saint John's Bible.

00:54:06.640 --> 00:54:08.300
Here's our sower and the seed.

00:54:08.300 --> 00:54:09.830
And this page was done backwards,

00:54:09.830 --> 00:54:12.740
because almost always the
calligraphy was done first,

00:54:12.740 --> 00:54:15.320
and then the artist
did his or her work.

00:54:15.320 --> 00:54:18.440
But Sally was ready -- wasn't ready
to write, and the artist was ready

00:54:18.440 --> 00:54:20.740
so they did the artwork first,
and then Sally wrote around it.

00:54:20.740 --> 00:54:23.280
And when she got to the
bottom of this column,

00:54:23.280 --> 00:54:25.310
she discovered something
pretty terrible.

00:54:25.310 --> 00:54:28.590
This column ended up one
line longer than this column.

00:54:28.590 --> 00:54:30.780
She had left out an entire line.

00:54:30.780 --> 00:54:35.040
And they would have had to have
scraped a fourth of the page off,

00:54:35.040 --> 00:54:36.340
and they couldn't do this.

00:54:36.340 --> 00:54:39.090
And Sally said, "I was pretty
sure I was about to lose my job."

00:54:39.090 --> 00:54:40.390
And Donald said, "Don't worry,

00:54:40.390 --> 00:54:43.230
we're going to fix it the same
way they did centuries ago."

00:54:43.230 --> 00:54:44.530
So look at the page.

00:54:44.530 --> 00:54:46.330
As you read down the column --

00:54:46.330 --> 00:54:58.030
[ Silence ]

00:54:58.030 --> 00:55:01.800
You come to a tiny red
triangle right there.

00:55:01.800 --> 00:55:05.380
That red triangle points
back to the bird.

00:55:05.380 --> 00:55:09.260
The birds feet are holding the
rope, the rope travels down,

00:55:09.260 --> 00:55:12.840
and it's wrapped around the
line which is missing saying,

00:55:12.840 --> 00:55:14.520
"Oops, it belongs up there."

00:55:14.520 --> 00:55:18.580
So you read it, and the
crowd came together again,

00:55:18.580 --> 00:55:19.930
so that they [whistles]
could not even eat.

00:55:19.930 --> 00:55:23.320
When it's finally heard, they
went out to restrain him.

00:55:23.320 --> 00:55:24.620
Isn't that wonderful?

00:55:24.620 --> 00:55:30.430
That is a legitimate way of
fixing a mistake in a manuscript.

00:55:30.430 --> 00:55:34.190
And they've done it
that way for centuries.

00:55:34.190 --> 00:55:40.320 position:56%
Here's a book of ours from the
Walters Art Museum Collection that's

00:55:40.320 --> 00:55:41.630
several centuries old.

00:55:41.630 --> 00:55:44.260
And look at that little monk.

00:55:44.260 --> 00:55:49.790
He's saying, "Oops, this
line belongs up there."

00:55:49.790 --> 00:55:51.090
Isn't that wonderful?

00:55:51.090 --> 00:55:52.390
I love that one.

00:55:52.390 --> 00:55:53.690
This is how they've
done it for centuries.

00:55:53.690 --> 00:55:54.990
Because you can't just
toss these away.

00:55:54.990 --> 00:55:57.350
Out of 1130 pages, we
have nine corrections.

00:55:57.350 --> 00:55:58.650
Isn't that amazing?

00:55:58.650 --> 00:55:59.950
How many mistakes on
the last email you sent?

00:55:59.950 --> 00:56:01.250
I mean, think about that.

00:56:01.250 --> 00:56:02.550
[Laughter] Yes.

00:56:02.550 --> 00:56:03.850
One of my favorites is this one.

00:56:03.850 --> 00:56:05.150 position:56%
Look at the bumblebee at the bottom.

00:56:05.150 --> 00:56:06.450 position:56%
[Laughter] He's attached to a pulley
system pulling it up into place.

00:56:06.450 --> 00:56:07.750
And this is a fantastic one too.

00:56:07.750 --> 00:56:09.050
[Laughter] There's a little lemur,
which does not come from Minnesota,

00:56:09.050 --> 00:56:10.350
but he's doing his job as well.

00:56:10.350 --> 00:56:11.650
&gt;&gt; There's a theological
art effect too.

00:56:11.650 --> 00:56:12.950
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Yes.

00:56:12.950 --> 00:56:14.250
&gt;&gt; There is a wideness
in that [overlapping] --

00:56:14.250 --> 00:56:15.550
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: Very much so.

00:56:15.550 --> 00:56:16.850
In fact --

00:56:16.850 --> 00:56:18.150
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:56:18.150 --> 00:56:19.450
Yes; one of the biggest
discussions was,

00:56:19.450 --> 00:56:20.750
"Should we make them
redo these pages?"

00:56:20.750 --> 00:56:22.050
And it was one of our
oldest monks that said, "No.

00:56:22.050 --> 00:56:23.350
We have the Word of God.

00:56:23.350 --> 00:56:24.650
Let's take every chance
to admit we're human."

00:56:24.650 --> 00:56:25.950
And so they have.

00:56:25.950 --> 00:56:27.510
Sally Mae Joseph was the artist
that made the very first mistake

00:56:27.510 --> 00:56:29.170
in the Saint John's
Bible that was there.

00:56:29.170 --> 00:56:32.280
And she said, "I felt just awful.

00:56:32.280 --> 00:56:33.580
Here I am doing this."

00:56:33.580 --> 00:56:36.580
Until Donald Jackson
made the second mistake.

00:56:36.580 --> 00:56:39.980
And she said, "That was the day I
got [inaudible] there was a god,"

00:56:39.980 --> 00:56:41.280
she said.

00:56:41.280 --> 00:56:43.820
[Laughter] As you go
all the way through.

00:56:43.820 --> 00:56:49.100
We could spend hours talking
about the pages of the Bible.

00:56:49.100 --> 00:56:52.180
We could spend hours taking
a look at how, you know,

00:56:52.180 --> 00:56:56.800
ancient stories are brought to
life weaving in beautiful context

00:56:56.800 --> 00:57:02.680
where you have the Christ family
tree, acknowledging the fact

00:57:02.680 --> 00:57:05.850
that we share common
roots, beginning with Jesus,

00:57:05.850 --> 00:57:10.510
all the way back to Abraham, with
Sarah, and also Hagar listed.

00:57:10.510 --> 00:57:13.130
[ Silence ]

00:57:13.130 --> 00:57:16.010
The Saint John's Bible
welcomes those traditions.

00:57:16.010 --> 00:57:20.140 position:56%
Do you notice the structure of the
family tree is written on a menorah.

00:57:20.140 --> 00:57:23.740
And that menorah is lit
with Islamic Arabesques.

00:57:23.740 --> 00:57:26.340
Behind it a swirling mandala.

00:57:26.340 --> 00:57:28.630
Beneath it -- or connecting all --

00:57:28.630 --> 00:57:32.740
everything over here
together to a Christian cross.

00:57:32.740 --> 00:57:36.380
Acknowledging the fact that
we all share a common root,

00:57:36.380 --> 00:57:38.620
back to Abraham.

00:57:38.620 --> 00:57:41.220
The Saint John's Bible
weaves in modern science.

00:57:41.220 --> 00:57:43.540
Look at the background
of this artwork,

00:57:43.540 --> 00:57:46.950
and you will see very clearly
that in the modern world yes,

00:57:46.950 --> 00:57:49.750
we understand our genealogy
as a family tree,

00:57:49.750 --> 00:57:55.060
but we also understand
it through our DNA.

00:57:55.060 --> 00:57:56.790
The entire background
of the Saint John's --

00:57:56.790 --> 00:58:00.020
of this artwork is over a
pattern of beautiful DNA.

00:58:00.020 --> 00:58:03.270
And the DNA is absolutely
everywhere.

00:58:03.270 --> 00:58:06.100
The Saint John's Bible is
an amazing work of art.

00:58:06.100 --> 00:58:08.450
And you've heard the story of this.

00:58:08.450 --> 00:58:11.750
But one thing that's really unique
about the Saint John's Bible is

00:58:11.750 --> 00:58:16.640
that for one of the first
times in the manuscript world,

00:58:16.640 --> 00:58:19.720
a commission like this is done.

00:58:19.720 --> 00:58:22.960
It was finished on May 9th, 2011.

00:58:22.960 --> 00:58:24.680
We wrote the last words.

00:58:24.680 --> 00:58:28.790
It took 23 individual
artists 15 years to create.

00:58:28.790 --> 00:58:34.330
At the same time the original
was being made, Saint John said,

00:58:34.330 --> 00:58:39.540
"We have to find a way to
share it beyond our doors."

00:58:39.540 --> 00:58:45.650
And so we created the finest fine
art edition we can possibly imagine

00:58:45.650 --> 00:58:52.220
of a lithograph copy on paper
that recreates the look, the feel,

00:58:52.220 --> 00:58:56.750
the texture -- oh I guess
the quality of longevity

00:58:56.750 --> 00:58:58.580
of the inks and the materials.

00:58:58.580 --> 00:59:00.680
It recreates a texture of the gold.

00:59:00.680 --> 00:59:03.070
Even the fiber of the
paper is designed

00:59:03.070 --> 00:59:06.310
to mimic the way the velum turns.

00:59:06.310 --> 00:59:09.950
And these 299 copies, the
final editions are known

00:59:09.950 --> 00:59:11.660
as "The Heritage Edition."

00:59:11.660 --> 00:59:14.890
And the Library of Congress and the
American people have been given one

00:59:14.890 --> 00:59:18.280
of those fine art editions,
called "The Apostles Edition".

00:59:18.280 --> 00:59:19.580
And it was delivered.

00:59:19.580 --> 00:59:22.610 position:56%
I had the privilege of delivering --
and I skipped a couple things here.

00:59:22.610 --> 00:59:26.530
I had the privilege of delivering
this volume when it was brought

00:59:26.530 --> 00:59:30.090
to the Library of Congress in --

00:59:30.090 --> 00:59:32.280
a few months ago when
Pope Francis was here.

00:59:32.280 --> 00:59:35.160
And it was delivered and
given to the American people.

00:59:35.160 --> 00:59:38.820
Today you have two of those
volumes which have been delivered.

00:59:38.820 --> 00:59:42.640 position:56%
Over the next few -- several
months, all seven will be delivered.

00:59:42.640 --> 00:59:48.210
I will create a permanent home here
at the Library of Congress as well.

00:59:48.210 --> 00:59:49.510
&gt;&gt; You'll be delivering this?

00:59:49.510 --> 00:59:50.810
&gt;&gt; Tim Ternes: I will be
delivering each volume.

00:59:50.810 --> 00:59:52.200
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:59:52.200 --> 00:59:54.100
That's up to Mark.

00:59:54.100 --> 00:59:55.930
[Laughter] Trust me, because
I've only scratched the surface

00:59:55.930 --> 00:59:57.370
on the stories that I know.

00:59:57.370 --> 00:59:59.820
I know I have gone a bit longer
than I said I would, Mark.

00:59:59.820 --> 01:00:01.120
I'm sorry.

01:00:01.120 --> 01:00:03.080
But if there are any questions, I
will stick around and answer them,

01:00:03.080 --> 01:00:04.380
if we want to answer them now.

01:00:04.380 --> 01:00:08.470
But I want you to think about
one thing before you close today.

01:00:08.470 --> 01:00:12.450
The Saint John's Bible is
this incredible work of art.

01:00:12.450 --> 01:00:17.340
But as I've said many times, it is
a complete waste of time, money,

01:00:17.340 --> 01:00:20.190
and talent if it's never used.

01:00:20.190 --> 01:00:24.310
In a thousand years from now, I
don't want to see a clean book.

01:00:24.310 --> 01:00:27.490
I want to see it ripped.

01:00:27.490 --> 01:00:29.770
I want to see it licked.

01:00:29.770 --> 01:00:31.440
I want to see the pages explode.

01:00:31.440 --> 01:00:33.270
Sorry, Mark.

01:00:33.270 --> 01:00:34.810
[Clears Throat] [Laughter]
I want to see it used.

01:00:34.810 --> 01:00:37.170
Because the legacy of the Saint
John's Bible won't be the fact

01:00:37.170 --> 01:00:38.470
that we made it.

01:00:38.470 --> 01:00:41.040
The legacy of the Saint John's
Bible will be what we choose

01:00:41.040 --> 01:00:42.620
to do with it.

01:00:42.620 --> 01:00:43.920
So do something with it.

01:00:43.920 --> 01:00:45.220
If nothing else, just enjoy it.

01:00:45.220 --> 01:00:47.020
Thank you very much for
your time here today.

01:00:47.020 --> 01:00:51.830
